'''Murray McCheyne Thomson''' {{post-nominals|OC}} was born in December 19, 1922<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lumley|first1=Elizabeth|title=The Canadian Who's who|date=2000|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=0802049397|page=1257}}</ref> in [[Henan|Honan, China]] where his parents were Christian missionaries.<ref>[http://www.quaker.org/peaceweb/poquak01.html Murray Thomson at Peaceweb/Peace/Ottawa]</ref> Thomson has founded many non-profits in Canada.<ref name="utpress">{{cite web|url=http://www.utpress.utoronto.ca/cgi-bin/cw2w3.cgi?p=thomson&t=12509&d=1424|title=Canadian Who's Who 1997 entry|accessdate=April 4, 2006}}</ref> He was the 1990 recipient of the [[Pearson Medal of Peace]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://207.112.105.217/PEN/1991-02/sharpe.html |title=Murray Thomson: Ottawa's Peace Medal Winner |last=Sharpe |first=Alan |date=February 1991 |publisher=Peace and Environment News |access-date=1 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="PBIC" /> for his work in [[peacekeeping]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dennisgruending.ca/2012/12/murray-thomson-peace-activist-at-90/ |title=Murray Thomson, peace activist at 90 |last=Gruending |first=Dennis |date=8 December 2012 |access-date=1 August 2016}}</ref> and was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in 2001.<ref name="OC Announcement">http://archive.gg.ca/media/doc.asp?lang=e&DocID=380</ref><ref name="OC page">http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=139&t=12&ln=Thomson</ref> He has also been awarded the Canadian awards of the Golden Jubilee Medal<ref>http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=40482&t=6&ln=McCheyne%20Thomson</ref> and the Diamond Jubilee Medal<ref>http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=104861&t=13&ln=Thomson</ref><ref>http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=40482&t=6&ln=McCheyne%20Thomson</ref> He is a former Executive Director of [[CUSO]].<ref name="PBIC" />

He is credited in helping the formation of:
* [[Grindstone Island]]{{cn|date=March 2018}}
* [[The Peacefund Canada Foundation]] (1980s)<ref name="PBIC">{{cite web | last=Watson | first=Rick | title=The Peacefund Canada Foundation | website=Peace Brigades International Canada | url=http://www.pbicanada.org/index.php/en/take-action-2/donate-2/the-peacefund-canada-foundation-2 | access-date=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref name="OC page" />
* [[Peace Brigades International]]<ref name="OC page" /><ref name="PBIC" /> (1981)
* [[Project Ploughshares]]<ref name="OC page" /><ref name="PBIC" /> (1976)
* [[Canadian Friends of Burma]]{{cn|date=March 2018}} (1991)
* [[Canadians for a Nuclear Weapons Convention]]{{cn|date=March 2018}} (2012){{cn|reason=uncertain|date=March 2018}}

Murray is a recognized international expert and advisor to governments, aid organizations, and lobbyists on [[disarmament]] and [[arms control]].<ref name="OC page" />
He was significantly involved starting the United Nations World Disarmament Campaign and drafting its policy document of which was passed by the United Nations General Assembly.<ref name="OC page" />
He has continued to be active in advocating for [[disarmament]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Canada must join new negotiations to eliminate nuclear weapons | website=Canadians for a Nuclear Weapons Convention | date=1 January 2017 | url=http://nuclearweaponsconvention.ca/2017/02/01/cnwc-statement-hill-times/ | access-date=1 February 2018}}</ref>
In 2017, he led a campaign among members of the Order of Canada in calling for an international Nuclear Weapons Convention. Over 1,000 members of the order signed the petition.<ref>{{cite web | title=Welcome | website=Canadians for a Nuclear Weapons Convention | date=1 December 2016 | url=http://nuclearweaponsconvention.ca/2017/01/01/welcome/ | access-date=1 February 2018}}</ref>

