The '''Over Thirty Months Scheme''' is a scheme to keep older cattle out of the human foodchain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stats.oecd.org/glossary/detail.asp?ID=6768|title=Over Thirty Months Scheme|date=13 July 2005|publisher =[[OECD]]}}</ref> It is based on the "Over Thirty Months Rule" introduced in the UK on 3 April 1996, as one of several measures to manage the risk associated with [[bovine spongiform encephalopathy]] (BSE).
By November 1997, about 1,772,000 cows had been slaughtered under the scheme, with compensation of 1 [[European Currency Unit|ecu]] per kg, reduced to .9 ecu in October 1996, and later to .8 ecu, and later still a 560&nbsp;kg cap per animal.<ref>{{Cite Hansard|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1997/nov/26/over-30-months-scheme|speaker=Paul Keetch|date=26 November 1997|house=Commons|volume=301|col=1058|title=Over-30-months Scheme}}</ref>
The [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] reviewed the scheme in 2003, in view of the steps taken to date, and the introduction of EU testing and inspection regime in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalsoced.org.uk/330_OverThirtyMonthsOTMRuleReview.html|title=Over Thirty Months (OTM) Rule Review}}</ref>
In November 2004 ''[[Farmer's Weekly]]'' announced that [[DEFRA]] intended to scrap the scheme "as early as July 2005".<ref>http://www.fwi.co.uk/business/the-end-is-in-sight-defra-to-scrap-over-30-months-scheme.htm</ref> The scheme was finally abolished in November 2005.<ref>{{Cite document|title=BSE and Beef New Controls Explained|page=5|url=http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/multimedia/pdfs/publication/bsebooklet.pdf|accessdate=21 May 2015|publisher=Food Standards Agency}}</ref> At the same time it became illegal to send cattle born before August 1996 to an abattoir for human consumption.
